==English==

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|la|applaudere||to clap the hands together, applaud}}, from {{m|la|ad||to}} + {{m|la|plaudere||to strike, clap}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əˈplɔːd/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈplɔd/|lang=en}}
* {{a|cot-caught}} {{IPA|/əˈplɑd/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-applaud.ogg|Audio (GA)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɔːd|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[applause|Applause]]; applauding.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[plaudit|Plaudit]].

====Related terms====
* {{l|en|applause}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive}} To [[express]] [[approval]] (of something) by [[clap|clapping]] the [[hand]]s.
#: ''After the performance, the audience '''applauded''' for five minutes''.
# {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive}} To [[praise]], or express approval for something or someone.
#: ''Although we don't like your methods, we '''applaud''' your motives.''
#* Shakespeare
#*: By the gods, I do '''applaud''' his courage.
